model.dek: Condé Nast Traveler readers rate the top resorts in Santa Rosa Beach, Orlando, Naples, Lake Buena Vista, Key West, Boca Raton, Fort Lauderdale, Miami Beach, Miami, Amelia Island, Palm Coast, and more

memberComments.comment: "Love sipping mojitos by the pool and enjoying the ocean views from the spacious rooms."
"Tucked away, golf, spa, restaurants and shopping close by."

"An outstanding full service resort; wonderful accommodations beach or bayside, with full kitchens and in-suite laundry machines. The staff is outstanding, from check-in through bell and wait staff, restaurant and poolside and beach staff.  Many many tennis courts, some lit for evening play, multiple golf courses of varying degrees of difficulty, miles of white sandy beach and calm Gulf waters, a full indoor spa with fitness club, wonderful weather, nearby cosmopolitan Sarasota with arts, culture, theatre and music. A major airport is just 15 minutes away and a short 2 hour flight non stop from New York City."
"Great Experience. They offered everything you would want on a vacation. The staff showed a high level of customer service."

"I've stayed in tons of hotels in Miami since I was a child, but the Acqualina Resort and Spa is by far the best hotel. The staff, resort and spa are the top of the line and I continue to go back multiple times a year with my family."
"Time and time again this property never fails...consistently excellent in all facets. Service, accommodations, friendliness, food...it's the best!"
"If you play golf, you have to stay here."

"The Arnold Palmer Hotel was the best experience that we have ever had traveling. The price was excellent, the atmosphere was luxurious, the staff friendly and helpful, location was convenient. Top notch place!"
"It's Disney! If I could, I'd visit every month to get my mouse fix. Love Ohana for breakfast & lunch. Beautiful grounds and great staff… and it's on the monorail route!"
"Fun resort lush and tropical for a central Florida location. Don't miss Ohana Disney character dining at this resort with Lilo and Stitch."

"Staying at The Villas of Grand Cypress makes the Orlando experience. In a normally busy/hectic city this property is quiet and serene - you almost forget you are minutes away from the crowded theme parks."
"Great golf. Very nice bar and restaurant."

Nothing comes close to the ambience of the Vinoy in St. Pete. The staff is consistently friendly and helpful, the verandah is extremely popular, and the location cannot be beat. We stay here every time and it has never disappointed.
What a find, just like stepping back in time but with all the current amenities. Enjoyed the water view and the absolutely gorgeous architecture.
A classic. Excellent in every way. Pool area worthy of Esther Williams!
Beautiful, historic, updated hotel with excellent service from front desk to fitness to room service.

Disney's Animal Kingdom Lodge is an oasis in the middle of a tourist area that can sometimes seem hectic and daunting. We booked a Savannah room, which had a balcony overlooking the savannah. Each moving, we woke up to the sun rising above the trees, and animals everywhere, roaming free. I spent a lot of time sitting on the balcony with a coffee as I watched zebras and giraffes meander through the savannah. After fun, but long, days in the Disney parks, coming back to the hotel was like being on a whole, separate vacation.

The views are spectacular! Having a Savannah room just can't be beat. Where else in the US can you see giraffes from your hotel balcony? Our five-year-old son loved it! And, Boma has one of the best buffets at Disney.
So nice to be able to park the car here and take Disney's transportation to-and-from the parks every day. Our kids loved the pools and white sand beach.
A world within 'The World'—and just a short walk from Epcot and Hollywood Studios.

Of all the Disney Resorts we've stayed at, the Boardwalk Inn is our favorite.  The location is supreme--just a walk or ferry ride to Epcot or Hollywood Studios; plus the restaurants in the Boardwalk area are the best--especially the New York Strip at the Flying Fish Cafe, one of the best kept secrets in the 'World.'

Gorgeous hotel, felt like the heyday of the Jersey Boardwalk, yet with all the modern accoutrements we don't want to live without. Wonderfully comfortable beds and cute Juliet balcony overlooking a serene grassy courtyard yet so close to Epcot.

If you're going to Disney you can't beat the Grand Floridian. Location, location, location! Great pools and views of the Magic Kingdom.  Your can watch fireworks from you balcony and there's great entertainment in the lobby nightly.
Disney at its best.  Service, location to parks, restaurants are all top of the line.
Great beach and facilities especially the kiddie pool. Excellent food and service.

Pool personnel were particularly wonderful especially with the kids.  Many activities available to occupy all ages. Food choices, however, were very limited.  If one stays there more than a day, you should leave the hotel to find different meal choices.

A fun place to stay; the location is amazing! You can watch the water parade from the beach.  We stayed in a 2-bedroom villa and it was immaculate. Very spacious for our family of 5 and the washer and dryer were great to have.  We will definitely return.
This is an excellent Disney Resort located near the Contemporary and very close to the Magic Kingdom. It is modeled after the lodges of Yellowstone National Park.
An experience you'll never forget. Our twins were greeted each morning by name and loved the sandy-bottom pool.
Nothing compares to the elegance and comfort here—it's simply the best around.
Friendly and right on the beach.  Delicious breakfasts in the morning and wine  and cheese in the evening.
Excellent B&B. Inn keepers go out of their way to make you feel at home. Breakfasts are better than mom's.
Terrific serviceÑbut beware, a short trip to the pool might become an all-day pleasure!
My 8-year-old grandson was given the Royal TreatmentÑthe staff is top-notch.
A quaint hotel with historical significance and a  beautiful setting.
A beautiful property with an ideal location and amenities. There's even an indoor pool for the rare, cold day in Florida.
The private, 'Adults Only' pool is so appreciated at this lovely resort with lots of activities for all.

I have stayed at LaPlaya several times; it's a hospitable resort that offers easy access to fun beach activities. The food is delicious, even the business meeting catering had interesting and tasty snacks.  The staff are always attentive and professional.

The service was phenomenal and the staff was extremely friendly and accommodating. The grounds are impeccably kept. The housekeeping staff was very, very efficient. It will be our only choice when in Naples.
This was a great find. When you stay here you get a pass to go on a fast lane for all the rides. There was a water taxi to the parks. Great theme pools too.

A great family resort with nice dining options and a fun pool complex. We are annual pass holders to Universal and enjoyed five trips this year to Loews Universal hotels. Take the rickshaw bike ride if the ferry is too crowded.
This a great hotel!  The facilities, the gardens, the beach area and pool are all perfectly pristine.  The feel is more of a private condominium and not that of a sterile hotel room.
Beautiful location, great beach, best Italian food I've ever eaten at Sal e Pepe.

I went with my mother for my birthday (mother/daughter trip) and I had the time of my life!  The staff deserves many thanks because they were amazing.  On the first night, we walked into our room to find complimentary wine and sweet treats with a birthday card.  Absolutely, amazing!  My mother and I will be back and this time with the whole family.
A one of a kind island experience. Spacious rooms, excellent dining options, an expansive spa and one of the best beaches in Florida.

The staff has the right mix of customer service and efficiency. The rooms are beautiful. I have stayed there multiple times and have never been disappointed in either the service or the room. I don't stay anywhere else when I go to Key West and always recommend the Ocean Key to other travelers.
A beautiful little hotel with great location and comfortable updated rooms.  We had a wonderful time enjoying happy hour by the pool.
Very 'retro' and visually pleasing with a fabulous restaurant, Azurea.
Would go back time and time again. Design is incredibly beautiful and innovative, service was impeccable, and the spa was beautiful.
On the ocean; great views. Renovated rooms were very nice. Good spa, good restaurants, great staff.
Beautiful. We loved the location, beach, pool, etc.  Stayed on the Club Level which you can't top.
Simply a terrific property. Great service, rooms, food and the spa is amazing. Highly recommended.
Lovely property.  Club level amenities are unbeatable.
Excellent, beautiful, classy.  A real Ritz-Carlton experience. The Fazio golf course is amazing,  the pro shop staff and golf management staff more than accommodating.
One of our favorite locations. Traditional Ritz service and environment with access to the beautiful beach club location on the key. Great, friendly service without a stuffy attitude.

We have stayed at the Royal Pacific Resort twice in the past year. The resort is stunning, service is great, food is excellent and you can't beat the ferry or walking path to both of the Universal parks.
Great place to stay while visiting Universal or Islands of Adventure theme parks.  You can't beat the ferry boat transportation and fast passes for rides.
The epitome of luxury with superb customer care. Ring the 'Sunset Bell' at dusk, toast s'mores around the campfire, watch a movie by the pool, or play a game of life-size chess on the lawn.
An outstanding experience, from the moment you arrive to the moment you depart, regretfully. A memorable and special experience.

fields.title: [The Biltmore Hotel](http://www.biltmorehotel.com/)
fields.caption: This iconic Coral Gables resort has launched a “Fore Your Improvement” package that includes three hours of pro instruction, video swing analysis, and unlimited play on the Donald Ross Classic course. And since golf isn’t limited to dads, the package, which starts at $569 a night including breakfast, is open to anyone.

items.name: The Resort at Longboat Key Club
Acqualina Resort & Spa on the Beach
Arnold Palmer's Bay Hill Club & Lodge
Villas of Grand Cypress Golf Resort, Orlando
The Vinoy Renaissance St. Petersburg Resort & Golf Club
Elizabeth Pointe Lodge
items.description: This Nantucket Shingle lodge with sweeping rooflines and broad porches is in a "great location right on the beach"—"the place took me back to the Gatsby era." The "incredible, awesome lodgings" include rooms in the Main House with period antiques and oversized tubs, and mini suites in the Ocean House that exhibit West Indies decor and have oceanview decks facing the Atlantic. Wood floors, brass lighting, and a fireplace mark public areas. Enjoy breakfasts that "are better than Mom’s" each morning and wine and hors d’oeuvres during a social hour in the evening. "The innkeepers go out of their way to make you feel at home."

items.name: LaPlaya Beach & Golf Resort
items.description: This beachfront resort is a "classic Florida beauty filled with easy elegance." Baleen serves dinner inside or outside by the ocean and has "delicious, well-prepared Gulf Coast food and service." Staff are "attentive and willing to help in any situation that may arise." The "impeccably kept grounds" include coconut palms, tiki torches, and a fire pit surrounded by Adirondack chairs. The Bob Cupp–designed golf course is "the best in Florida—and I have played many." Choose a Gulf Tower room with a balcony to watch "the memorable sunsets."

items.name: Little Palm Island Resort & Spa
items.description: Guests are welcomed with tropical rum punch and their names on wooden plaques on their rooms at this "very private and isolated resort," accessible only by boat or seaplane. The crushed-seashell paths and more than 250 Jamaican coconut palms make guests feel like they are "in the South Pacific." Housing four-poster beds and outdoor showers, renovated thatched-roof bungalows in British colonial decor lack phones, televisions, or clocks, making them "wonderful places to relax and reconnect." The "food is expensive but marvelous" at the restaurant, which serves French and pan-Latin dishes with the occasional wild card, hence Peking duck foie gras and yellowtail snapper seviche. "The staff are the best."

items.name: Ponte Vedra Lodge & Club
items.description: This small property is "on the prettiest beach in Florida, with gorgeous views from every suite," ergo the perfect location score. Twenty miles from historic St. Augustine, it was built to resemble a Mediterranean villa and has Spanish mission accents: a terra-cotta roof, stucco exterior, stone fountains, and wrought iron lampposts. Accommodations come with floral bedding and curtains and four-poster beds. Have lunch outdoors—fish tacos and ahi tuna salad—under beige and green umbrellas at the casual Oasis, then sit indoors at the Innlet for a more formal dinner of fresh seafood like bourbon-marinated Atlantic salmon or Cajun-seared mahimahi. Expect "phenomenal service."

items.name: Loews Portofino Bay Hotel at Universal Orlando
Marco Island Marriott Beach Resort, Golf Club & Spa
items.description: On the largest of the Ten Thousand Islands, at the southwestern tip of Florida 17 miles from Naples, this Balinese-style beach resort was designed to be a "Hawaii of the East Coast." A four-year, $225 million renovation that wrapped up in 2009 resulted in rooms kitted out with dark mahogany-wood furnishings and red and gold accents. Kurrents, the show-kitchen signature restaurant, serves steak, seafood, and Floridian cuisine with pan-Asian elements; Korals, the cocktail and sushi bar, has floor-to-ceiling windows overlooking the Gulf.

items.name: Ocean Key Resort & Spa
items.description: This "top-of-the-line destination" on historic Duval Street near Mallory Square has guest rooms that reflect their environment through bright blues and greens, with furnished balconies providing panoramic views of the Gulf of Mexico. "They’re nice, but I think they looked a little better on the Internet." Hot Tin Roof serves Cuban-influenced dishes like pork chicharrónes, baked goat cheese, paella, and crab-stuffed lobster; "it’s a great place to watch the sunset." SpaTerre uses oils, herbs, and volcanic clays from Java, Bali, and Thailand in its treatments. "It’s the little touches that make the service so good."

items.name: Ritz-Carlton, Amelia Island
items.description: Anticipate "stylish ambience, classical music overhead, and fabulous artwork in the halls" at this oceanfront resort on a northeast Florida barrier island. Shaped like a horseshoe, the eight-floor property is "perfect for a family getaway," overlooking sand dunes and an "exceptional beach." "Large and nicely appointed" rooms in soft green, gold, and lavender hues have mahogany floors and floor-to-ceiling balcony doors with plantation shutter panels, as well as "the most comfortable beds ever." Dine on beef tenderloin, Maine lobster, or wild salmon by the ocean’s edge at Salt, "our all-time favorite restaurant," or enjoy a more casual coastal menu at Café 4750. "All of our expectations were exceeded by the excellent service and attention to detail."

items.name: Ritz-Carlton, Fort Lauderdale
items.description: Melding the brand’s urbanity with the town’s identity as a top yacht market and cruise port, the 187-room Ritz-Carlton (a former St. Regis) resembles a glossy Art Deco ocean liner, from its curvilinear marble lobby, filigreed banisters, and velvet taupe banquettes, to the seventh-floor pool deck that gives guests a sight line straight into the ocean. Room decor is simple, with beige upholstery and dark wood, and floor-to-ceiling windows overlooking the Atlantic or the Intracoastal Waterway. A can-do attitude, rare in South Florida, makes up for any service missteps: When one guest lost her valet ticket and the hotel’s inability to locate her car threatened to make her late for an appointment, a chauffeur drove her in the house Bentley. Oceanfront Cero is a romantic dinner spot but shockingly overpriced for breakfast. And the hotel would do well to provide free chairs and towels on the beach, instead of leaving guests to be accosted by umbrella vendors. But quibbles aside, and taking into account the W hotel flanking this one, you’ll want to be the first on your block to catch the up-trend wave in Fort Lauderdale.

items.name: Ritz-Carlton Golf Resort,  Naples
items.description: "My husband calls it his second home—doesn’t he just wish. . . . " This "golfer’s paradise," on the 36-hole Greg Norman–designed Tiburón Golf Course, has Mediterranean-style architecture and lodge-style interior decor. Rooms have Frette linens, marble double vanities, goose-down comforters, shades of burgundy and gold, and views of the course. At Lemonía, the European and Moroccan dishes can be taken indoors or alfresco; order the signature burger at the Poolside Grill. The Eye Wonders program teaches children about the universe.

items.name: Ritz-Carlton, Naples
items.description: This U-shaped property with two orange Mediterranean-style towers overlooks the Gulf of Mexico and is near the Naples Zoo. Antiques and artwork embellish interiors, as do Waterford chandeliers and Asian carpets. The resort’s daily interactive environmental programs for children include nature walks, microscope time in the kid-size lab, and field trips. Rooms in buttercream and light green have dark-wood furniture. Nibble on fresh nigiri rolls at the Sushi Bar; Gumbo Limbo’s bar is "the best place for a burger on the beach. I also love to drink something tall and cool, and order the Key lime pie there—it’s the best around—while watching the sun set!"

fields.caption:
**


Party places** It’s hard to forsake the sand itself, but for brides who’d rather walk the aisle in heels, the two-story Beach House combines a water’s edge setting with polished wood floors and floor-to-ceiling windows. Other options: Center Court, a large sun-dappled plaza with an ornate fountain, and the Tea Garden, a lush pocket of manicured hedges and palms. Or take it inside to one of three ballrooms, where you can hang flower arrangements from the ceiling and have the dance floor embellished with your monogram. 




**For guests on a budget** A mile from the Gulf, the Inn at Pelican Bay offers great rates and free transportation to the sand.




******One more thing** If you’re looking for a little extra excitement, the Ritz-Carlton’s frosting phenom, executive pastry chef Sebastien Thieffine, will decorate your cake in the reception area while guests watch.
fields.title: [The Ritz-Carlton](/hotels/north-america/united-states/ritz-carlton-naples-naples-florida)

items.name: Loews Royal Pacific Resort at Universal Orlando
Sandpearl Resort
items.description: "You would think you were on a tropical island" at the former Clearwater Beach Hotel, now an LEED Silver–certified beach resort within walking distance of Clearwater’s strip of restaurants and bars and Pier 60. "Welcoming, comfortable rooms" are decorated in sandy hues with orange and yellow highlights, dark wood furniture, local art, and balconies that showcase "heavenly sunsets night after night." The dining at Caretta on the Gulf includes a seasonal menu, sushi, and mostly organic produce. For a more laid-back meal, enjoy specialties like pulled pork roasted in-house at Tate Island Grill, just inches from the sand. "The A+ service is prompt and pleasant."

items.name: St. Regis Bal Harbour Resort
items.description: A 243-room beach resort 30 minutes from Miami International Airport but far above Floridian norms, with a Jean-Georges restaurant and a sublime spa.

items.name: Sunset Key Cottages (Luxury Collection)
items.description: "A charming cottage community on Sunset Key, away from the noise and crowds," "it’s worth every penny for the private-island feel and escape." Reachable by boat, just off Key West, the resort is "surrounded by turquoise water, white sand, and tropical flowers." Wake up in one of the 40 cottages to "a picnic basket with breakfast waiting on your front porch." Each residence has a Victorian tin roof and is bright with warm butter yellows, blues, stripes, and floral prints. Latitudes, serving local seafood, is "the most romantic place" thanks to its beachfront and alfresco dining.

items.name: The Breakers Palm Beach
items.description: Inspired by the Italian villas of the fifteenth century and modeled on the Villa Medici in Rome, this historic hotel, built by Henry Morrison Flagler, has "timeless Italian Renaissance–style architecture." "The opulent public areas are exquisitely appointed and feel special." The "stunning location right on top of the ocean" makes it "a romantic getaway." Rooms are simple, with light-blue and light-green color schemes; artwork offers a glimpse into the past. Oceanview rooms "are absolutely fabulous." Dining options include The Circle, where Sunday brunch is served under a 30-foot frescoed ceiling. A crew of 44 maintain the 140 landscaped acres.

items.name: WaterColor Inn & Resort
items.description:
This Panhandle property has "beautiful surroundings"—it’s among sand dunes near the restaurants and shops of Seaside. The four-story inn’s rooms are done in soft blues and greens and have floor-to-ceiling windows that afford "gorgeous views of the Gulf of Mexico." Adults can make use of the complimentary kayaks or rent stand-up paddleboards while kids take part in Camp WaterColor—"it’s an excellent family facility with upscale amenities." Farm-to-table options at Fish Out of Water are served on a sunset deck overlooking the Gulf, while the Gathering Spot offers more casual beach fare and a sushi bar. "Homemade cookies are delivered to your room with the nightly turndown by the accommodating staff. Naughty but nice!"

A much-loved Panhandle favorite, set amidst tall sand dunes near the restaurants and shops of Seaside’s planned community (3rd and 4th floor rooms have prime Gulf views, bungalows have outdoor showers and small courtyards). Activities include canoeing, kayaking, stand-up paddle boarding, and electric boating on the Western Lake as well as biking through woodland forests when folk aren’t lazing on the broad swath of sand on their doorstep.

**Party places** While we can’t imagine not wanting to marry in front of that brilliant emerald water, there are plenty of lush lawns and gardens as well. Then it’s on to poolside cocktails, a tented dinner on the Inn’s green, or something small and charming at the BoatHouse. And the new LakeHouse should open this year, allowing you to host drinks, dinner, dancing, and after-party all in one location.

**For guests on a budget** WaterColor’s huge pool of rental homes means your pals can bunk together; additionally, wedding guests can receive up to 20 percent off the regular rates.

**One more thing** Children go bananas for this place (cookies at turn-down each night, a superlative kids’ club), so by all means make this a family affair.
